  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a buzzword—it's something I've seen play out in my own community. Growing up in a neighborhood where many kids are the first in their families to go to college, I've noticed how the idea that 'girls aren't good at math' or 'people from my background don't belong in engineering' can really hold people back. My parents, one with a PhD and the other with a high school diploma, taught me early on that your worth isn't tied to your job title or your test scores. But in school, especially in STEM classes, that belief can become a real burden. When I was in high school, I remember a friend who was really good at coding but started avoiding group projects because she was afraid of being judged as 'not smart enough.' That's stereotype threat in action—when people internalize negative stereotypes about their group and it affects their performance. I think we absolutely should address it. The best way? Start with small, everyday actions: teachers who speak to students as individuals, parents who emphasize effort over outcomes, and communities that celebrate diverse strengths. In Philadelphia, where there's so much diversity, it's important to create spaces where everyone feels they belong. I’ve seen this in my own life through my kids—when they ask me about their math homework, I focus on their curiosity, not their mistakes. Stereotype threat isn't something that disappears overnight, but with consistent, compassionate effort, we can build a culture where everyone feels empowered to explore STEM without fear.",
